<BaseLayout
  title="Conveyor Motors & Drive Systems Guide | PackagingConveyor.com"
  description="Guide to conveyor motors and drives: AC induction, gear motors, servo motors, VFDs, MDR motors, drum motors, motor sizing methodology, and IE3/IE4 energy efficiency standards."
  canonical="https://packagingconveyor.com/resources/conveyor-motors-drives/"
  schema={[breadcrumbSchema, articleSchema, faqSchema]}
>

  <!-- ═══ HERO ═══ -->
  <section class="bg-blueprint relative overflow-hidden">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-16 sm:py-20 relative z-10">
      <nav class="text-sm font-mono text-white/60 mb-8" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/" class="hover:text-white/70">Home</a>
        <span class="mx-2">/</span>
        <a href="/resources/" class="hover:text-white/70">Resources</a>
        <span class="mx-2">/</span>
        <span class="text-white/70">Motors &amp; Drives</span>
      </nav>
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <div class="section-label text-accent-bright/80 mb-6">Resource Guide</div>
        <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl lg:text-7xl font-800 text-white tracking-wide uppercase leading-[0.95] mb-8">
          Conveyor Motors & <span class="text-accent-bright">Drives</span>
        </h1>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ AIO DEFINITION ═══ -->
  <article>
    <section class="py-12 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="aio-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <p id="aio-heading" class="text-lg text-ink leading-relaxed">
          Conveyor motors convert electrical power into the mechanical torque and speed that drive belts, rollers, and chains. The most common conveyor motor is the AC induction motor paired with a gear reducer (gear motor), controlled by a VFD (variable frequency drive) for adjustable speed. Servo motors provide precise position control for indexing conveyors. Motorized drive rollers (MDR) embed a brushless DC motor inside a conveyor roller for zone-based accumulation. This guide covers every motor and drive type used in packaging conveyor systems, including motor sizing methodology and energy efficiency standards (IE3/IE4/IE5).
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ AC INDUCTION MOTORS ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="ac-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Motor Types</div>
        <h2 id="ac-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          AC Induction <span class="text-accent">Motors</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            AC induction motors are the workhorse of the conveyor industry. They run on standard 208V, 230V, or 460V three-phase power (or 115V/230V single-phase for fractional HP motors). The motor has no brushes, commutator, or permanent magnets — the rotor turns by electromagnetic induction from the stator winding. This simple construction makes AC induction motors reliable, inexpensive, and low-maintenance.
          </p>
          <p>
            Standard AC induction motors run at near-synchronous speed: approximately 1,750 RPM for a 4-pole motor on 60 Hz power. This speed is far too fast for direct conveyor drive. A gear reducer (gearbox) between the motor and the drive pulley reduces speed and multiplies torque. Gear ratios of 10:1 to 60:1 are common, producing output speeds of 30-175 RPM at the drive pulley shaft.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Gear Motors</h3>
          <p>
            A gear motor integrates the AC motor and gear reducer into a single unit. This eliminates the coupling, mounting bracket, and alignment issues of separate motor and gearbox combinations. Gear motors are the standard drive for conveyor systems. Three gear reducer types dominate conveyor applications:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-8 space-y-2">
            <li><strong>Helical gear reducers</strong> — high efficiency (96-98% per stage), smooth operation, low noise. Available in inline (shaft-in, shaft-out) and right-angle configurations. Helical gear motors are available from all major power transmission suppliers.</li>
            <li><strong>Worm gear reducers</strong> — compact, lower cost, right-angle output as standard. Lower efficiency (50-90% depending on ratio) than helical gears. The worm gear is self-locking at high ratios (40:1 and above), preventing the conveyor from backdriving — useful for incline conveyors. Worm gear motors are widely available from multiple suppliers.</li>
            <li><strong>Planetary gear reducers</strong> — highest torque density (smallest size for a given torque rating), high efficiency, inline configuration. Higher cost than helical or worm types. Used where space is constrained or high torque is required in a compact package.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Motor Enclosures</h3>
          <p>
            Motor enclosure type matches the operating environment. TEFC (Totally Enclosed Fan Cooled) is the standard for dry industrial environments. TENV (Totally Enclosed Non-Ventilated) eliminates the external fan for applications where fan debris or noise is a concern. Washdown duty motors use stainless steel housings, sealed bearings, and IP65 or IP69K ratings to withstand high-pressure washdown. Explosion-proof motors (Class I/II, Division 1/2) are required in environments with flammable dust or vapors. The <a href="/resources/conveyor-design-guide/components/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">components guide</a> covers enclosure and frame material selection in more detail.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ VFDs ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="vfd-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Speed Control</div>
        <h2 id="vfd-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Variable Frequency <span class="text-accent">Drives</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            A VFD (variable frequency drive) controls AC motor speed by converting incoming fixed-frequency AC power to variable-frequency, variable-voltage output. Adjusting the output frequency changes the motor's synchronous speed — 30 Hz produces half speed, 60 Hz produces full speed, 90 Hz produces 1.5x speed (within motor thermal limits). VFDs are the standard method for adjustable-speed conveyor operation.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">VFD Benefits for Conveyors</h3>
          <p>
            VFDs provide soft starting — the motor accelerates gradually instead of starting at full speed. Soft starting reduces mechanical shock on belts, couplings, and gearboxes, and limits inrush current to 100-150% of rated current (versus 600-800% for across-the-line starting). VFDs allow speed matching between conveyors and packaging machines — the PLC sends a speed reference to the VFD, and the VFD adjusts motor speed in real time. Dynamic braking through the VFD provides controlled deceleration without mechanical brakes.
          </p>
          <p>
            VFDs save energy on conveyors that run at variable speeds or partial loads. Motor power consumption follows the cube law — a motor running at 50% speed consumes approximately 12.5% of full-speed power. Conveyors that run slower during low-production periods realize significant energy savings with VFDs compared to fixed-speed operation.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">VFD Selection</h3>
          <p>
            Size the VFD for the motor's full-load amperage (FLA) plus a margin for overload. Standard-duty VFDs handle 110% overload for 60 seconds. Heavy-duty VFDs handle 150% overload for 60 seconds — required for conveyors with frequent starts/stops or high-inertia loads. When selecting a VFD, ensure it supports the required communication protocol for PLC integration — Ethernet/IP, PROFINET, or EtherCAT — and that it matches the conveyor motor's full-load amperage with appropriate overload margin.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Decentralized VFDs</h3>
          <p>
            Decentralized (motor-mounted) VFDs mount directly on the motor or gear motor, eliminating the long motor cable run from a central control panel. This reduces cable cost, reduces electrical interference, and simplifies installation. Decentralized VFDs are offered by most major drive suppliers as an alternative to panel-mounted drives. Decentralized drives suit conveyor systems with many individual drives spread over a large area — common in distribution and fulfillment centers.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ SERVO MOTORS ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="servo-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Precision Control</div>
        <h2 id="servo-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Servo <span class="text-accent">Motors</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Servo motors provide precise speed, position, and torque control through closed-loop feedback. A high-resolution encoder on the motor shaft reports position to the servo drive, which adjusts motor current thousands of times per second to maintain the commanded position. Servo motors accelerate and decelerate faster than induction motors, making them the choice for indexing conveyors that must start, stop, and position product at exact locations.
          </p>
          <p>
            Packaging applications for servo-driven conveyors include: indexing product under filling heads, positioning cartons for labeling or printing, synchronizing conveyor speed to wrapper or shrink tunnel speed via electronic gearing, and registering products to a fixed pitch for robotic pick-and-place. Servo systems are available from all major automation platform vendors, and selecting a servo system that matches the existing PLC platform simplifies integration and programming.
          </p>
          <p>
            Servo systems cost significantly more than VFD-driven induction motors — the servo motor, servo drive, feedback cables, and programming time all add to the investment. Use servo drives only where the application requires positioning accuracy better than &plusmn;1mm, rapid acceleration/deceleration, or electronic synchronization with other axes. For simple variable-speed transport, a VFD-driven induction motor is more cost-effective. The <a href="/resources/conveyor-design-guide/conveyor-engineering/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">engineering calculations guide</a> covers motor sizing formulas applicable to both induction and servo motor systems.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ MDR MOTORS ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="mdr-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Embedded Drive</div>
        <h2 id="mdr-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Motorized Drive <span class="text-accent">Rollers</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            A motorized drive roller (MDR) is a conveyor roller with a brushless DC motor and planetary gear reducer built inside the roller tube. The MDR replaces an external motor, gearbox, belt, and chain — the entire drive system fits inside a standard 50mm (1.9-inch) diameter roller. MDR motors run on 24V DC power and are controlled by zone controller cards that manage accumulation logic.
          </p>
          <p>
            Each conveyor zone (typically 18-36 inches long) has one MDR that drives 2-5 adjacent idle rollers via O-ring or poly-V belts. A photoeye sensor at each zone detects product presence. When a zone is occupied and the downstream zone is also occupied, the zone controller stops the MDR — holding the product in place without contact pressure. When the downstream zone clears, the MDR restarts to advance the product. This provides zero-pressure accumulation without a central PLC. For more on MDR conveyor systems, see the <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR conveyors page</a>.
          </p>
          <p>
            MDR systems are energy-efficient because only zones with product are powered. A 100-foot MDR conveyor with 30 zones might have only 5-10 zones active at any time, consuming a fraction of the power that a continuously running line-shaft or belt-driven roller conveyor would use. MDR conveyors are also quiet — operating at 50-60 dBA versus 70-80 dBA for chain-driven roller conveyors.
          </p>
          <p>
            MDR rollers are available in standard and high-speed variants from several global suppliers, with torque ratings from 0.3 Nm to 2.5 Nm. High-torque MDR rollers handle loads up to 150 lbs per zone. <!-- VERIFY: maximum MDR zone load varies by manufacturer model — confirm with current catalogs -->
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ DRUM MOTORS ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="drum-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Integrated Drive</div>
        <h2 id="drum-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Drum <span class="text-accent">Motors</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            A drum motor integrates the electric motor and gear reducer inside the drive pulley (drum) of a belt conveyor. The motor, gearbox, and bearings are sealed inside a stainless steel or aluminum shell filled with oil for lubrication and cooling. No external motor, gearbox, guards, or chain are required — the drum motor is the drive pulley.
          </p>
          <p>
            Drum motors are ideal for sanitary and washdown environments because there are no external moving parts to guard or protect from water. The sealed construction eliminates nip points at the drive, prevents contamination from external lubricants, and withstands IP66/IP69K high-pressure washdown. Drum motors suit food-grade belt conveyors, inspection conveyors, and compact conveyors where space for an external motor is not available.
          </p>
          <p>
            Drum motor sizes range from 80mm (3.15 inches) to 800mm (31.5 inches) in diameter, with power ratings from 0.05 HP to 15 HP. Small-diameter drum motors enable tight-radius belt conveyors for close-gap product transfers.
          </p>
          <p>
            One limitation of drum motors: the motor is not field-serviceable. When a drum motor fails, the entire unit is replaced. Spares inventory must include a replacement drum motor — rebuild turnaround time from the manufacturer can take weeks. For detailed parts and spares planning, see the <a href="/resources/conveyor-parts/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor parts guide</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ DC MOTORS ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="dc-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Motor Types</div>
        <h2 id="dc-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          DC <span class="text-accent">Motors</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            DC motors were once the standard for variable-speed conveyor drives. DC motor speed is controlled by varying the armature voltage — simpler electronics than VFDs but requiring more motor maintenance (brushes and commutator wear). Brushed DC motors are now largely replaced by AC motors with VFDs for main conveyor drives.
          </p>
          <p>
            Brushless DC (BLDC) motors remain widely used in MDR rollers and small conveyors. BLDC motors have no brushes or commutator — electronic commutation provides long life, high efficiency, and low maintenance. 24V BLDC motors power MDR conveyor zones, small tabletop conveyors, and conveyor accessories (pop-up transfers, pusher diverters). The low voltage (24V DC) simplifies wiring and improves safety compared to 480V AC systems.
          </p>
          <p>
            90V DC gear motors are still found on older conveyor systems and on new conveyors where simple, low-cost speed control is needed. A DC motor controller (SCR drive) provides speed adjustment from a potentiometer or analog signal. 90V DC gear motors are still available from several motor suppliers. When replacing an aging DC drive system, VFD-driven AC motors are the recommended modern equivalent — they provide the same speed adjustability with lower maintenance. For maintenance considerations when upgrading drive systems, see the <a href="/resources/conveyor-maintenance/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor maintenance guide</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ ENERGY EFFICIENCY ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="efficiency-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Standards</div>
        <h2 id="efficiency-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Energy <span class="text-accent">Efficiency</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Motor efficiency determines how much electrical energy is converted to mechanical output versus heat loss. Higher-efficiency motors reduce energy costs and run cooler, extending insulation and bearing life. International standards define motor efficiency classes to enable comparison across manufacturers.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">IEC Efficiency Classes</h3>
          <p>
            The IEC 60034-30-1 standard defines four efficiency classes for AC induction motors: IE1 (Standard Efficiency), IE2 (High Efficiency), IE3 (Premium Efficiency), and IE4 (Super Premium Efficiency). In the United States, NEMA Premium Efficiency aligns with IE3. The U.S. Department of Energy mandates minimum IE3/NEMA Premium efficiency for most general-purpose motors since 2011 (amended in subsequent rulemakings). IE4 motors exceed these minimums and provide additional energy savings — typically 1-2% higher efficiency than IE3 at rated load.
          </p>
          <!-- VERIFY: exact DOE rulemaking dates for motor efficiency standards — verify against current Federal Register -->

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Motor Sizing and Efficiency</h3>
          <p>
            Motor efficiency drops when the motor operates below 50% of rated load. An oversized motor running at light load wastes energy through higher iron losses and lower power factor. Proper motor sizing — using the belt pull and HP calculations from the <a href="/resources/conveyor-design-guide/conveyor-engineering/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">engineering calculations guide</a> — ensures the motor operates near its rated load where efficiency is highest.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">VFD Impact on Efficiency</h3>
          <p>
            VFDs introduce harmonic distortion and switching losses that reduce overall system efficiency by 2-5% compared to direct-on-line operation at the same speed. At reduced speeds, the energy savings from lower speed far outweigh the VFD losses. The net result is lower energy consumption for variable-speed applications. For fixed-speed conveyors running at the motor's rated speed, a VFD provides soft starting benefits but no energy savings at steady state.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Synchronous Reluctance and PM Motors</h3>
          <p>
            IE5 (Ultra Premium Efficiency) targets are driving adoption of synchronous reluctance (SynRM) and permanent magnet (PM) motors for conveyor applications. SynRM and PM motor packages delivering IE5-level efficiency are now offered by several major drive suppliers. These motors require a matched VFD (they cannot run across-the-line) but provide 3-5% higher efficiency than IE3 induction motors at rated load, with even larger gains at partial load and reduced speed. The higher motor cost is offset by energy savings over the 10-20 year motor life.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ MOTOR SIZING ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="sizing-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Engineering</div>
        <h2 id="sizing-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Motor Sizing <span class="text-accent">Methodology</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Motor sizing for conveyors follows a four-step process: calculate belt pull, calculate theoretical HP, apply service factor, and select the next standard motor size. The complete formulas and worked examples are in the <a href="/resources/conveyor-design-guide/conveyor-engineering/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">engineering calculations guide</a>. This section summarizes the key points specific to motor selection.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">HP Formula</h3>
          <div class="bg-surface p-6 border-l-4 border-accent font-mono text-base">
            HP = (Te &times; V) / 33,000
          </div>
          <p>
            Where Te = effective tension (belt pull) in pounds and V = belt speed in feet per minute. This yields the theoretical HP at steady state. Multiply by the service factor (1.5 normal, 2.0 heavy, 2.5+ severe) and round up to the next NEMA standard motor size.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Gear Ratio Selection</h3>
          <p>
            The gear ratio determines the output RPM from the motor RPM. Target the output RPM to produce the desired belt speed on the specified drive pulley diameter. Use the belt speed formula: V = &pi; &times; D &times; RPM / 12. Solve for RPM: RPM = (V &times; 12) / (&pi; &times; D). Then calculate the gear ratio: GR = Motor RPM / Required Output RPM. Select the nearest available gear ratio from the manufacturer's catalog. VFDs compensate for gear ratio mismatch by adjusting motor speed.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Torque Verification</h3>
          <p>
            After selecting the motor and gear reducer, verify that the output torque exceeds the required torque. Required torque (in-lbs) = Te &times; D / 2, where Te is belt pull in pounds and D is drive pulley diameter in inches. The gear motor's rated output torque must exceed this value by the service factor margin. Check the gear reducer's thermal rating as well — continuous operation at or near maximum torque can overheat the gear oil.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Common Questions</div>
        <h2 id="faq-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Motors & Drives <span class="text-accent">FAQ</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <details open class="border border-ink/10 bg-surface-dim p-6">
            <summary class="font-display text-lg font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer">What type of motor is used on a conveyor?</summary>
            <p class="mt-4 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
              Most packaging conveyors use AC induction gear motors — an AC motor integrated with a gear reducer. For variable speed, a VFD controls motor speed electronically. Servo motors handle precise indexing and positioning. MDR (motorized drive roller) motors use 24V brushless DC motors inside conveyor rollers for zone-based accumulation. Drum motors integrate the motor and gearbox inside the drive pulley for washdown belt conveyors.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details class="border border-ink/10 bg-surface-dim p-6">
            <summary class="font-display text-lg font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer">What is a VFD and why is it used on conveyors?</summary>
            <p class="mt-4 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
              A VFD (variable frequency drive) controls AC motor speed by varying the output frequency and voltage. VFDs enable adjustable conveyor speed, soft starting, speed matching between conveyors and machines, and energy savings at reduced speeds. Select a VFD that supports the required PLC communication protocol and matches the motor's full-load amperage with appropriate overload capacity.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details class="border border-ink/10 bg-surface-dim p-6">
            <summary class="font-display text-lg font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer">What is an MDR motor?</summary>
            <p class="mt-4 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
              An MDR motor is a brushless DC motor and planetary gear reducer built inside a conveyor roller. Each zone has one MDR driving adjacent idle rollers. MDR systems provide zero-pressure accumulation, low noise, and energy efficiency because only active zones are powered. When specifying MDR rollers, compare torque ratings, speed ranges, and zone controller compatibility across available suppliers.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details class="border border-ink/10 bg-surface-dim p-6">
            <summary class="font-display text-lg font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer">How do you size a motor for a conveyor?</summary>
            <p class="mt-4 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
              Calculate belt pull from conveyor length, load, friction, and elevation. Apply HP = (belt pull &times; belt speed) / 33,000. Multiply by service factor (1.5 normal, 2.0 heavy duty). Round up to the next standard NEMA motor size. Verify output torque exceeds required torque. See the <a href="/resources/conveyor-design-guide/conveyor-engineering/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">engineering calculations guide</a> for detailed formulas and examples.
            </p>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

